  "prompt": "What's the difference between \u51e0 and \u591a\u5c11 in the following sentences?",
  "response": "In Mandarin Chinese, both \"\u51e0\" (j\u01d0) and \"\u591a\u5c11\" (du\u014dsh\u01ceo) are used to ask about quantities, but they are used in different contexts and have different implications.\n\n1. **\u51e0 (j\u01d0):**\n   - \"\u51e0\" is typically used when you expect the number to be relatively small, usually less than ten. \n   - It is often used for asking about a specific, small quantity and is usually followed by a measure word. \n   - Example: \"\u4f60\u6709\u51e0\u4e2a\u82f9\u679c?\" (N\u01d0 y\u01d2u j\u01d0 g\u00e8 p\u00ednggu\u01d2?) - \"How many apples do you have?\" (expecting a small number of apples).\n\n2. **\u591a\u5c11 (du\u014dsh\u01ceo):**\n   - \"\u591a\u5c11\" can be used for both small and large numbers, and it does not imply any expectation of size.\n   - It is used for asking about an unknown quantity that could potentially be large or when there is no expectation of quantity.\n   - Example: \"\u4f60\u6709\u591a\u5c11\u94b1?\" (N\u01d0 y\u01d2u du\u014dsh\u01ceo qi\u00e1n?) - \"How much money do you have?\" (no expectation of a small or large amount).\n\nIn summary, use \"\u51e0\" for small, expected numbers and \"\u591a\u5c11\" for any number, especially when there's no assumption about size.",
